<!-- Install -->
<section id="install">
  <h2>Install in one command</h2>
  <p class="section-sub">Single binary. Zero dependencies. Under 30 seconds.</p>
  <div class="install-box">
    <div class="cmd-row">
      <code id="cmd-curl">curl -fsSL https://pilotprotocol.network/install.sh | sh</code>
      <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCmd('cmd-curl',this)">Copy</button>
    </div>
    <p>Detects your platform, downloads a single binary (~10 MB), writes config, and starts the daemon.</p>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--muted)">Or with pip: <code style="color:var(--accent)">pip install pilotprotocol</code> &middot; Python 3.10+</p>
  <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--muted);margin-top:8px">Set a hostname: <code style="color:var(--accent)">curl ... | PILOT_HOSTNAME=my-agent sh</code></p>
</section>

<!-- FAQ -->
<section>
  <h2>FAQ</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q">Does Pilot replace MCP?<svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></button>
      <div class="faq-a"><p>No. MCP handles tool access (databases, APIs, file systems). Pilot handles agent-to-agent communication. They are complementary &mdash; MCP is vertical (agent to tool), Pilot is horizontal (agent to agent). Use both.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q">How long does it take to set up?<svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></button>
      <div class="faq-a"><p>Under 30 seconds. One command installs the binary, generates your identity, and starts the daemon. No configuration files to write, no ports to open, no cloud accounts to create.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q">Do I need a public IP or open ports?<svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></button>
      <div class="faq-a"><p>No. Pilot handles NAT traversal automatically &mdash; STUN discovery, UDP hole-punching, and relay fallback. Your agents connect directly even behind corporate firewalls and carrier-grade NAT.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q">Is it encrypted?<svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></button>
      <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes, always. X25519 key exchange and AES-256-GCM encryption on every connection. Agents are private by default and require mutual trust establishment before any data flows.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q">What languages are supported?<svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></button>
      <div class="faq-a"><p>The daemon is a single Go binary. Client libraries exist for Go (native) and Python (pip install pilotprotocol). The CLI works from any language that can shell out to pilotctl.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q">How is this different from the existing MCP + Pilot blog post?<svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"/></svg></button>
      <div class="faq-a"><p>This page focuses on the practical networking problem: crossing NATs, no public IPs, zero config. The <a href="/blog/mcp-plus-pilot-tools-and-network">blog post</a> covers the conceptual architecture of combining tools and network capabilities.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

